{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480511"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:45:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:45:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"60"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"60","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/60"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.48,0.09,0.06,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"60"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115479"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"60","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/60"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"60"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97482"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"2777"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"630"},{"type":"contributions","id":"830"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11181"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12881"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15040"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22742"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32584"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41974"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49081"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115479"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old woman with an established diagnosis of essential hypertension presents for review of her blood pressure at the General Practice clinic. Today it is 160/100 mmHg, which was repeated twice in office and once with the nurse. Her blood pressure reading has not improved since her last review three months prior. She is currently on perindopril 5mg. She states she is compliant with her medication. She is a non-smoker and has been exercising three times a week. Her BMI is 23 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Her blood results, including renal function and electrolytes, are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increase dose of perindopril","Add amlodipine","Add carvedilol","Check compliance with her pharmacist","24 hour ambulatory blood pressure monitoring"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the current Australian guidelines for hypertension management (2016), blood pressure targets should be individualised through shared decision-making between patient and clinician, taking into account the potential benefits and harms of treatment, and reviewed regularly. In general, a target blood pressure of \u0026lt;140/90 mmHg is recommended for patients with uncomplicated hypertension. In patients at high of cardiovascular risk\u2014such as those with previous myocardial infarction or stroke, diabetes with microalbuminuria, moderate to severe CKD or familial hypercholesterolaemia\u2014more intensive systolic blood pressure targets (\u0026lt;120 mmHg) may be appropriate with careful patient monitoring. In this case a blood pressure target of \u0026lt;140/90 is appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf target blood pressure is not reached after three months with a first-line antihypertensive, such as an ACE inhibitor, best management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eadd a second drug from a different drug class \u003C/strong\u003Erather than \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreasing the dose of her current perindopril\u003C/strong\u003E. Current hypertension guidelines recommend combination therapy with a second agent rather than uptitrating the first medication to maximum dose, as this approach provides greater blood pressure reduction with fewer side effects. This is unlikely to be \u0027white coat hypertension\u0027 as the blood pressure has been measured at three different times during her visit to the clinic - and still remains elevated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe addition of a calcium channel blocker such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eamlodipine\u003C/strong\u003E to the existing ACE inhibitor is an effective drug combination, and appropriate as the next step in management. This is an effective combination for blood pressure control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E24 hour ambulatory blood pressure monitoring\u003C/strong\u003E will not aid with further management as she has been previously diagnosed with hypertension thus this is not a newly diagnosed hypertension. If she had more labile hypertension, at high risk of cardiovascular events, or is supected of orthostatic or episodic hypertension, than a 24-hour ambulatory blood pressure monitoring may be advised but the patient does not meet these recommendations in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarvedilol\u003C/strong\u003E may be suggested in patients with other indications, such as angina, or history of myocardial infarct present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough the patient reports that she is compliant with her medication, self-reported adherence can sometimes be unreliable. In patients whose blood pressure remains uncontrolled despite appropriate first-line treatment and no obvious secondary causes, it is reasonable to consider \u003Cstrong\u003Enon-adherence\u003C/strong\u003E as a potential contributor to treatment failure. However, in this scenario, the patient appears motivated, has made lifestyle changes, and there is no overt indication of poor adherence; therefore checking compliance is not the most appropriate next step compared to adding a second-line agent per guideline recommendations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to the pharmacological management it is important to continue lifestyle advice (exercise, smoking cessation) and manage any comorbidities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The addition of another drug from a different class of anti-hypertensives is preferable to increasing the dose of the first drug."],"references":["National Heart Foundation of Australia. Guideline for the diagnosis and management of hypertension in adults \u2013 2016 [Internet]. Melbourne: National Heart Foundation of Australia; 2016 [cited 2025 May 23]. Available from: https://assets.contentstack.io/v3/assets/blt8a393bb3b76c0ede/bltbf3d36e10b48f01f/65b0963ea933e532ae0286de/01_Hypertension-guideline-2016_WEB.pdf","Stapff M, Hilderbrand S. First\u2010line treatment of essential hypertension: A real\u2010world analysis across four antihypertensive treatment classes. The Journal of Clinical Hypertension. 2019;21(5):627-634.","O\u0027Callaghan C. Goh M. Rong P. Hypertension The difficult Decision. In Australian Family Physician. 2013: 42 (6). Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2013/june/hypertension"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97482"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"60"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97482"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T21:26:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T21:28:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"60"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115479"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":